\emph{Multiple Choice Question: Exactly ONE of the answers provided is
correct. There is no partial credit in this questions.}

To find the integral

\begin{align*}
\int x^2 e^{2x}\, dx
\end{align*} using integration by parts, the best choice for
\emph{u} and \emph{dv} in the first step would be

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{i.}\quad u=x, \ dv=xe^{2x}\,dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{ii.}\quad u=x^2, \ dv=e^{2x}\,dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{iii.}\quad u=xe^{2x}, \ dv=x\,dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{iv.}\quad u=e^{2x}, \ dv=x^2\,dx
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v.}\quad u=x, \ dv=e^{2x}\,dx
\end{align*}
